<h2>History & Origins of Napa Valley</h2>

<p>Napa Valley's winemaking story began in the 1830s when <strong>George Calvert Yount</strong> planted the region's first vineyard near what is now Yountville. However, it was <strong>Charles Krug's</strong> establishment of the valley's first commercial winery in 1861 that truly launched Napa's wine industry. German immigrant <strong>Jacob Schram</strong> founded Schramsberg in 1862, followed by other pioneering families including the Beringers (1876) and Inglenook's Gustave Niebaum (1879).</p>

<p class="bg-wine-50 text-wine-800">The late 19th century marked Napa's first golden age, with phylloxera devastating European vineyards and creating global demand for California wines. By 1889, there were over 140 wineries operating in the valley, producing wines that competed internationally.</p>

<p>Prohibition (1920-1933) nearly destroyed Napa's wine industry, reducing the number of wineries from 713 statewide to just 140. Only a handful survived by producing sacramental wines, including Beaulieu Vineyard under <strong>Georges de Latour</strong>, who hired legendary winemaker <strong>André Tchelistcheff</strong> in 1938.</p>

<h3>The Modern Renaissance</h3>

<p>Napa's renaissance began in the 1960s with <strong>Robert Mondavi's</strong> establishment of his eponymous winery in 1966, introducing innovative techniques and elevating California wine's profile. The pivotal moment came with the <strong>1976 Judgment of Paris</strong>, where Stag's Leap Wine Cellars' 1973 Cabernet Sauvignon and Chateau Montelena's 1973 Chardonnay defeated prestigious French wines in blind tastings.</p>

<p>In 1981, Napa Valley became the first American Viticultural Area (AVA) established in California, recognizing its unique terroir spanning 30 miles from San Pablo Bay to Mount Saint Helena. Today, the region encompasses <strong>16 sub-AVAs</strong>, each with distinct microclimates and soil compositions.</p>

<p class="text-wine-700">Modern Napa Valley produces over 4 million cases annually from approximately 45,000 acres of vineyards, with Cabernet Sauvignon comprising 60% of plantings. The region commands premium prices globally, with cult wines like Screaming Eagle and Harlan Estate achieving legendary status among collectors worldwide.</p>

