<p>Napa Valley's Mediterranean climate creates ideal conditions for premium viticulture, with warm, dry summers averaging 75-85°F during the day and cooling to 45-55°F at night. This dramatic diurnal temperature swing—often exceeding 30°F—preserves crucial acidity while allowing phenolic ripeness. Annual rainfall averages 35 inches, concentrated between November and April, followed by a bone-dry growing season that stresses vines beneficially. The valley receives approximately 2,800 sunshine hours annually, with vintage variation creating distinct characteristics: cooler years like 2010 and 2011 produced wines with higher acidity and elegant structure, while warmer vintages like 2013 and 2015 yielded more opulent, fruit-forward expressions.</p>

