<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon and Sonoma County Cabernet?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Valley Cabernets typically offer more concentrated, structured wines with darker fruit flavors and higher tannins due to the warmer climate and well-draining volcanic soils. Sonoma County Cabernets tend to be more elegant and food-friendly with brighter acidity and red fruit characteristics, particularly from cooler areas like Alexander Valley. Napa's mountain appellations like Howell Mountain and Diamond Mountain produce especially powerful, age-worthy expressions.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Napa Valley wine good for beginners, or should I start elsewhere?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Napa Valley produces excellent entry-level wines, particularly from established producers like Cakebread, Far Niente, or Frank Family who offer approachable styles with consistent quality. Start with Napa Valley Sauvignon Blanc or Chardonnay before moving to Cabernet Sauvignon, as the white wines showcase the region's terroir without overwhelming tannins. However, expect to pay premium prices even for entry-level Napa wines due to the region's prestige and high production costs.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Why are Napa Valley wines so expensive compared to other California regions?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Land prices in Napa Valley average $300,000-$500,000 per acre, making it some of the most expensive vineyard real estate in the world. The region's strict agricultural preserve laws limit development and maintain scarcity, while the global reputation commands premium pricing. Additionally, many Napa producers use expensive French oak barrels, low-yield farming practices, and hand-harvesting, all contributing to higher production costs that are reflected in bottle prices.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Which Napa Valley sub-appellations offer the best value for money?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Calistoga and Pope Valley typically offer the best value among Napa sub-appellations, producing high-quality wines at lower prices than Rutherford or Oakville. Coombsville, Napa's newest AVA, also presents excellent value with distinctive volcanic soils producing elegant wines from producers like Farella and Coombsville Vintners. Avoid the ultra-premium appellations like Pritchard Hill or Atlas Peak if you're seeking value, as these command the highest prices in the valley.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How long should I cellar Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon before drinking?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Most Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignets benefit from 5-10 years of cellaring to allow tannins to soften and complex tertiary flavors to develop. Reserve bottlings and mountain-grown Cabernets can age gracefully for 15-25 years, while entry-level Napa Cabernets are often designed for consumption within 3-7 years. Store at 55°F with consistent temperature and humidity, as Napa's powerful wines need proper conditions to reach their full potential.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when buying Napa Valley wine?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common mistake is assuming all Napa Valley wines are created equal and buying based solely on the appellation name rather than the specific producer and vineyard site. Many mass-market brands use the Napa Valley designation while sourcing from less prestigious areas or using industrial winemaking methods. Always research the producer's reputation, specific vineyard sources, and winemaking philosophy rather than relying on the Napa Valley label alone.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the best alternatives to Napa Valley if I want similar quality at lower prices?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Paso Robles produces excellent Cabernet Sauvignon with similar power and concentration at 30-50% less cost, particularly from producers like Daou and L'Aventure. Washington State's Columbia Valley offers structured, age-worthy Cabernets from wineries like Quilceda Creek and Leonetti at competitive prices. For a closer geographic alternative, consider Lake County or Pope Valley wines, which often showcase similar terroir characteristics to Napa but without the premium pricing.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I decant Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon, and for how long?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Young Napa Valley Cabernet Sauvignon (under 5 years) typically benefits from 1-2 hours of decanting to soften tannins and open up the wine's aromatics. Older vintages (10+ years) should be decanted more gently and for shorter periods (30-45 minutes) to avoid over-oxidation, as mature wines can be fragile. High-altitude mountain Cabernets often require longer decanting due to their intense concentration and firm tannin structure.</p>
